# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: seafield-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Plans for the complex were announced in 2010.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The facility, which cost £15 million to construct, opened in December 2013.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It was the first healthcare facility to be completed in Scotland under the hub framework of the Scottish Futures Trust.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village, which is designed to offer services to 700 patients a day, contains 275 rooms including three dental suites, two minor procedure rooms and 29 consulting rooms.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Services being run from the health village include: cardiac rehabilitation, dentistry, dietetics, physiotherapy, podiatry, radiology, sexual health, speech and language therapy and minor surgery.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] An endoscopy service was provided from June 2014.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village acts as an educational resource for patients, carers and community-based staff.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] The health village also provides improved access to community based learning opportunities for healthcare professionals such as general practitioners (GPs) and GP trainees.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] Work on a mural on the side of the building began in July 2021.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-health-village] It is being painted by Fanakapan, a London-based artist, as part of the 2021 NuArt Festival.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital has its origins in the a small facility established at Guestrow in 1870.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] It moved to Barrett's Close in 1893 and to Castle Street in 1900.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The move to a new building, which was designed by James Brown Nicol and built between 1934 and 1937, formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by Professor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] An ante-natal hospital was added in 1941 and the facility joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The hospital progressed to stage two accreditation of the Baby Friendly Hospital Initiative in July 2011.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Construction of new hospital buildings - for The Baird Family Hospital and Anchor cancer centre - was delayed after costs escalated from £163m to £223m.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] In February 2020, forecast completion dates were 2022 and March 2023 respectively.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The Department of Obstetrics and Gynaecology, University of Aberdeen, is based at the hospital, which conducts a variety of research with an emphasis on obstetric epidemiology (including maternal mortality and morbidity), infertility and the prevention of cancer in women.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Aberdeen is also particularly known for its research into multiple pregnancy.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The associated **Dugald Baird Centre for Research on Women's Health** was set up in 1995 and is primarily a research unit, with consultative and teaching responsibilities.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] Current work focuses on a number of themes in reproductive health research and methodological development in evaluation.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-maternity-hospital] The centre is named after Sir Dugald Baird (1899–1986), Regius Professor of Midwifery at the University of Aberdeen from 1937 to 1965.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The **Aberdeen Royal Infirmary** (**ARI**) is the largest hospital in the Grampian area, located on the Foresterhill site in Aberdeen, Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI is a teaching hospital offering tertiary care for a population of over 600,000 across the north-east of Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] It offers all medical specialities with the exception of heart and liver transplants.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Aberdeen Royal Infirmary has it origins in a facility established at Woolmanhill in 1739.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The move to the current site formed part of the Aberdeen Joint Hospitals Scheme as envisaged by the Scottish doctor Matthew Hay, which involved the development of an integrated medical campus at Foresterhill.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The granite buildings on the site were designed by James Brown Nicol.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital was officially opened by the Duke and Duchess of York on 23 September 1936—King Edward VIII had been due to open the infirmary but he called off his visit and instead went to Ballater railway station to meet the American socialite Wallis Simpson off her train.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The first patients were admitted a month later.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital joined the National Health Service in 1948.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In the 1980s the English physicist John Mallard led a team which built the first whole body magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) scanner.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The world's first whole-body MRI scanner was used for diagnostic imaging between 1980 and 1983.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The prototype machine, Mark One, was put on display in the hospital's art gallery in February 2016.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Following fundraising by *Evening Express* readers, in 1992 a Siemens scanner costing £870,000 was brought.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1984, a hyperbaric oxygen unit was built for the treatment of decompression illness and the hospital's in vitro fertilisation unit achieved a number of successful pregnancies in 1985, its first year of operation.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 1986, a new £550,000 out-patient eye clinic opened, offering corrective laser eye surgery, and in 1989, the hospital introduced a breast cancer screening service for women over the age of 50, with X-rays taken every three years.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2013, a £110m emergency care centre development was completed.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] This was the first time that the Foresterhill campus had hosted emergency and urgent care facilities in the same building, and 75% of the beds in the centre are single-occupancy.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In February 2014, it was revealed that the hospital has a repairs backlog of £60 million.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] On 26 June 2014, John Swinney, the then Finance Secretary, announced a £120 million investment for a new cancer centre and maternity hospital on the site.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] In 2016, the ARI became one of four major trauma centres as part of a national major trauma network in Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] Social workers can be contacted in the hospital, and a branch of the Citizens Advice Bureau is based there.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by the volunteer-run radio station, Grampian Hospital Radio.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The hospital is served by several bus services with regular connections to Aberdeen city centre and service to places as far as Inverurie and Oldmeldrum in the north, Inverness in the West and Cove Bay in the south.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new multistorey carpark with space for over 1,000 cars was opened in 2017.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] There are close links with the University of Aberdeen's medical school and there has been pioneering research in many fields, including the development of MRI and positron emission tomography (PET) scanning.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] A new PET scanner was installed in 2006.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The ARI has been one of the centres evaluating telemedicine equipment and developing services in Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The Academy of Medical Royal Colleges and Faculties in Scotland produced a report entitled "Learning from serious failings in care" in July 2015.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The investigation was launched after scandals in the health service in 2013 and 2014 leading to concerns about patient safety and care at the infirmary.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] They found leadership and accountability were often lacking and bullying was endemic.
[src:seafield-hospital/aberdeen-royal-infirmary] The 20 recommendations for improvements in the NHS included a set of minimum safe staffing levels for consultants, doctors, nurses and other staff in hospital settings.
[src:seafield-hospital/aboyne-hospital] The facility, which was designed by Jenkins & Marr, opened as an infectious diseases hospital in 1898.
[src:seafield-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A ward pavilion was added in 1926 and, after the hospital had joined the National Health Service in 1948, a new health centre was added in 1980.
[src:seafield-hospital/aboyne-hospital] A major refurbishment started in 2002 and the newly modernised facilities were opened by Anne, Princess Royal in August 2003.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The origin of the name of the town is not entirely clear.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Although the folk etymology is that Buckie is named after a seashell (genus *buccinum*) the shared marine background is most likely a coincidence.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The name Buckie would not have originally identified a place immediately adjacent to the sea, so alternative etymological sources are more likely.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Unfortunately, in one of the earlier books on Scottish place names, Buckie on the Moray Firth does not receive a mention.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] However, a Buckie in the Balquhidder district of Perthshire is described as being derived from the Gaelic word *boc* or Welsh *bowk*, both meaning a buck or male deer.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This suggests the meaning of Buckie as *place where male deer gather*, possibly referring to the valley of what is known today as the Buckie Burn.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] A 1936 article by a Dr Cramond discusses the earliest mention of Buckie dating from 1362, when the lands of *Rove Bucky in le Awne* were leased by John Hay to John Young, vicar of Fordyce.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The Hays, from whom the Rannes family were descended, had acquired through Royal favour a footing in the district at a still earlier age when the greater part from the Deveron to the Spey was embraced in the Forest of Awne or Ainie (now Enzie) and the Boyne.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Rove Bucky is far from understandable and could be a scribe's error and should perhaps read Over Bucky as occurs in older title deeds, in distinction to Nether Buckie.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] It has been spelt in different ways, Robert Burns calling it Bucky in his song *Lady Onlie - Honest Lucky* as was common at the end of the 18th century.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Robert Gordon's map *Aberdeen, Banf, Murrey &c. to Inverness: [and] Fra the north water to Ross*, which is dated at some time between 1636 and 1652, shows Buckie in its own right as a community some small distance from the coast with the community of Freuchny sitting nearer the shore to the north.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Robert Gordon and Joan Blaeu's *Duo Vicecomitatus Aberdonia & Banfia, una cum Regionibus & terrarum tractibus sub iis comprehensis* published in Amsterdam 1654 clearly shows Buckie and Freuchny with the addition of Nether Buckie.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This community, which would later come to be known as Portessie, was reportedly formed when "Porteasie.....became a fishing station in 1727, when 5 houses were built by the proprietor of Rannes for the accommodation of the original fishers from Findhorn".
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The 1731 Rathven Session Minutes shows that Rotten Slough had a population of 40 with ten households while the 1791 entry records 177 persons in 44 households.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] By the time of the publication of the 1891 First Series Ordnance Survey Map of Elgin, which reflects the 1866-1870 survey, Buckie has developed markedly with areas named Seatown, Newtown, Ianstown and Portessie.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The 19th century OS Six Inch series further shows Gordonsburgh, Craig Bow and Strathlene.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The 1910 OS 3rd Edition one-inch map of Elgin has settled on the name of Ianstown and all other parts of Buckie are named as they are known today but then, just to confuse the issue, the Bartholomew Survey Atlas of Scotland, Edinburgh, 1912 uses the label *Ianston*.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The conflicting nomenclature continued with the issue of the 1929 OS One-inch Popular edition and the 1933 JG Bartholomew & Son, Half-inch to the Mile maps of Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The town lies on the Moray coast, around five miles east of the mouth of the River Spey.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] On the eastern side it largely comes to an end against the Freuchny burn, whilst the more central Buckie Burn divides Buckie and Buckpool.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie comprises numerous former separate fishing villages, each of which retain their own name and character.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie itself is the central part of the community lying between the Victoria Bridge under which flows the Buckie Burn at the western end of West Church Street, the eastern end of Cluny Harbour and above the shore area.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] West of the Buckie Burn is Buckpool, which was formerly known as Nether Buckie, and on the shoreline, west of Cluny Harbour, there is the Yardie.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Immediately above the Yardie on the Buckie side of the burn is Seatown.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] To the west of the Yardie is Harbourhead.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] To the east of Cluny Harbour lie Ianstown, Gordonsburgh and Portessie also known locally as *The Sloch* (historically *The Rotten Slough*), which reaches towards Strathlene.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The 2021 UK Census reported that, from Buckie's total population, 84.2% were born in Scotland with the largest single minority being those born in England (9.76%).
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] In terms of declared ethnicity, the largest was "White Scottish", at 84.25%.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Formerly part of the Moray constituency from 1983 to 2024, Buckie is now in the Aberdeenshire North and Moray East constituency for the UK Parliament, which returned the SNP MP Seamus Logan as its Member of Parliament in the 2024 General Election.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie is in the Banffshire and Buchan Coast constituency of the Scottish Parliament.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The seat was represented by SNP MSP Stewart Stevenson from 2011 until 2021 and by SNP MSP Karen Adam since the Scottish Parliament election of 2021.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The constituency is also part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Following the reorganisation of local government in Scotland, Buckie now has a multi-member ward with 3 councillors.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Additionally, there is the Buckie Community Council, which allows for 12 members to be elected or co-opted.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie is situated near the A98 primary road, which connects Fraserburgh with Fochabers at the junction of the A96.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The A98 runs east–west, approximately parallel with the southern edge of Buckie.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Where the A942 swings east, the A990 commences to the west and heads past The Yardie and onwards as Main Street and then Great Western Road towards Portgordon.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The nearest railway station is at Keith serving the Aberdeen-Inverness line.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Bus services operate to Aberdeen, Macduff and Elgin.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] A connecting service to Keith railway station was withdrawn when Moray Council funding ceased in September 2013, but it resumed in 2022 following local pressure.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Historically, Buckie had extensive rail connections with the rest of North East Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The Great North of Scotland Railway was laid out in the 1850s and served the Aberdeen to Inverness route until it was decommissioned in the late 1960s.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This construction did not reach the coast until Nairn and various branch lines were built to link the peripheral areas to the mainline service.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] In 1923, GNSR was absorbed into the London and North Eastern Railway before that itself was nationalised along with all other UK rail services into British Rail in 1948.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The Moray Coast Railway was also constructed by GNSR and the part of it that served Buckie, opening in 1886, ran from Cairnie near Keith down to the coast at Portsoy and then swung west through Cullen, Portknockie and Findochty reaching its first stop in Buckie at Portessie.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This station was built directly on top of the cliff and commanded panoramic views over the Strathlene House Hotel, Strathlene outdoor swimming pool and beach and onward to the offshore rocks of Craigenroan and the Moray Firth.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Indeed, a footpath led from the station down to the hotel and beach area and a visit to Strathlene was a popular day out by train before and during World War II.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] In 1936 Buckie Town Council proposed to change the name of the station to Strathlene but LNER declined suggesting instead that the Town Council erect their own large sign on Strathlene Golf Course that could be seen from the train.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] A retired passenger carriage was available for rent at the station.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] 1 mile (1.6 km) to the west was Buckie Station, which was located below the cliff and virtually across the street from Buckie Fish Market.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] To reach Buckie Station the railway gently descended to the west from the heights of Portessie on an embankment to the foot of the cliff whilst the parallel road lying adjacent to the track on its southern flank rose to the west up the *McLaren's Brae* end of East Church Street to the town centre.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] 1 mile (1.6 km) further west stood Buckpool Station and from there the line continued due west to Portgordon and onward to Spey Bay before crossing the River Spey and swinging inland to rejoin the mainline service at Elgin.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie was served by these three railway stations until 1968 when the line was finally closed.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] It is possible to walk, or cycle along the route of the old railway from Cullen to Garmouth.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This walk takes in the magnificent Cullen viaduct from which fine views of that town can be had and, at the other end, the Spey Bridge.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Portessie was also terminus to the Buckie and Portessie Branch of the Highland Railway.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This line was opened in 1884 and provided a direct rail link "up the hill" to Keith.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The line passed under a road bridge of what is now the A98, which has long since been demolished, and then turned westwards again towards Drybridge and made another sweep to the south as it passed Enzie and then headed uphill, over the Enzie Braes, to Aultmore and on to Keith.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This link was relatively short-lived and was closed in 1915 except for a freight service between Buckie and Portessie, which was closed in 1944.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The industrial centre of Buckie is based around Cluny Harbour.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This port was built by the Cluny family in 1877 to replace the town's first stone harbour in Nether Buckie, which was constructed in 1857 1 mile (2 km) west but had a tendency to silt up and become unusable.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The Laird of Letterfourie contributed £5,000 of the construction costs at Nether Buckie but the main investor with the balance of £10,000 was the Board of Fisheries.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Stevenson of Edinburgh, the family firm of the author Robert Louis Stevenson.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] It was and remains a very sturdily built edifice with the main walls of considerable thickness being built of quartzite, quarried locally at Strathlene, capped with a very hard type of sandstone, which was also used to form the walls at the entrance and of the harbour proper.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] As regards stability the harbour has remained a monument to engineering science with very little maintenance ever being necessary.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] It had a design fault, however, in that the entrance opened to the northeast and was subject to infill with shingle, moving westwards by longshore drift.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Later known as Buckpool Harbour, this earlier port became something of an eyesore and eventually the silted basin became overgrown and dangerously swampy.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The decision was taken to fill in the basin and this work was undertaken in the 1970s.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The resulting park includes a pebble beach and the original quartzite harbour walls remain completely intact.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Cluny Harbour was built by the Cluny family in 1877 at a cost of £60,000: at the time it was one of the finest harbours in Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Although Buckie was once a thriving fishing and shipbuilding port, these industries have declined.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Though Peterhead and Aberdeen are now more often associated with the fishing industry in northeast Scotland, in 1913 Buckie had the largest steam drifter fleet in Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Food processing remains important, with large fish factories and smoke houses found around the harbour.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie can properly be regarded as one of the main points of origin of the modern Scottish shellfish industry.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] He seized the opportunity to exploit this gap in the market and he built a thriving processing and packing business.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The Buckie Shipyard now repairs and refits RNLI lifeboats for much of the United Kingdom and operates service contracts for various other clients including the MoD as well as building new vessels but boatbuilding was a major industry in the town for decades.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Until recent years there were three separate boatyards building traditional wooden clinker fishing vessels.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Heading down North High Street, the view of the sea would have been interrupted by a huge grey corrugated iron shed.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This was Thomsons, from which vessels were launched directly into the Moray Firth from a slipway.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Heading east to Cluny Harbour was Herd and Mackenzie on the fourth or *lifeboat* basin of the harbour.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Directly behind their large sheds and across Blantyre Terrace was Jones with their private harbour into which they launched their vessels.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Thomsons is gone but the premises of Herd and McKenzie and Jones are part of the modern day Buckie Shipyard.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] It was Herd and McKenzie, a firm with its roots in Dunbartonshire from where Messrs Herd and Mackenzie sortied north, which built and launched the training schooner *Captain Scott* in 1972.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] At the time of its launch, this vessel was the largest of its type in the world.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] In earlier years, there were further boat construction operations dotted along the shoreline from The Yardie to Ianstown and on to Portessie but these had mostly been amalgamated into the three main firms or had gone out of business by the interwar period.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] A significant part of the population works in the offshore oil industry although Buckie somewhat missed the boat with the North Sea boom.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] In the late 1970s, there were extensive plans drawn up to extend Cluny Harbour out to the Mucks reef with the intention of serving oilfield supply vessels.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Nothing came of this but every now and then the idea rears its head once more to be met with great enthusiasm before failing to get off the ground again.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie was home to a specialist electric lamp factory of Thorn EMI until 1987 when it was closed and production moved to a new plant in Leicestershire.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] All of the predominantly female staff were offered jobs at the new facility in the East Midlands but, as the vast majority of the labour force were second wage earners in families, this offer was almost universally rejected.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie is home to the Inchgower Distillery, which sits 1 mile (2 km) or so inland from the town and is best known for the Inchgower Single Malt.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The fishermen are in a prosperous condition".
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The principal kinds of fish landed in Buckie for that year were herrings and all kinds of white fish.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] As a traditional fishing community, Buckie had an active religious life, and thus has numerous churches representing almost every branch of Northern European Christianity.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This twin-spired red sandstone construction was originally planned to act as the cathedral for the Roman Catholic Diocese of Aberdeen when it was opened in 1857.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This never came to pass and Buckie was left with what is arguably one of the grandest churches in NE Scotland outside of Aberdeen.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The basis of this reasoning was that the Roman Catholic population per capita in the area around Buckie was one of the highest in post-Reformation Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Gregory's, built at Preshome near Buckie in 1788, was the first post-Reformation church to be built in Scotland that looked like a church – prior to that date post-Reformation Roman Catholics worshiped in clandestine churches designed to look anonymous.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] These sometimes resembled farm buildings or ordinary houses, a superbly preserved example of this is St.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Ninian's (1775) at Tynet about 4 mi (6 km) to the west of Buckie, which looks like a long, low barn.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The largest Church of Scotland congregation in the town worships in the North Church in Cluny Square.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This building houses the town clock and was opened in 1879.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] There are other Church of Scotland congregations in addition to Methodist, Salvation Army, Episcopal, Baptist, Gospel Hall Brethren, Church of Christ and other congregational churches.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie High School is located on West Cathcart Street.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Examination results are in line with those of young people with similar needs and backgrounds in other schools across Scotland.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] There are four primary schools in Buckie - Cluny Primary School (Buckie Primary School until 1974) which is directly opposite the old building of the high school, Millbank Primary School on McWilliam Crescent off High Street, St.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Peter's RC Primary School in Buckpool and Portessie Primary School.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Additional primary schools in Portgordon, Findochty, Portknockie and Cullen contribute to the roll of Buckie High School.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The surrounding villages of Arradoul, Drybridge, Rathven and Lintmill, most of which once had their own schools, now send students to Buckie High School and nearby primary schools.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The adjoining school areas are Banff, Keith and Fochabers.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie has two golf courses, at the eastern and western peripheries.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] To the eastern extremity lies Strathlene Golf Course, which stretches almost all the way to the village of Findochty; while to the west lies Buckpool Golf Club, which reaches towards the village of Portgordon.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Adjacent to Buckie High School is Victoria Park, home of Buckie Thistle Football Club.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Although *The Jags* were consistently high finishers in the Highland Football League, the league title had eluded the club for decades until 2010, when an away win at Wick Academy F.C. sealed a first championship in 52 years.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The championship was retained in 2011 in the last match of the season, with Buckie scoring the winner in the final minute.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Since then the club has won the league twice more, in 2017 and 2024.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The 1950s was a decade when all trophies available were regularly won.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] During this era Buckie Thistle travelled to Hampden Park to meet Queen's Park in a Scottish Cup 4th round replay on 30 October 1954, winning 2–1, becoming the first and, to this day, only senior non-league club to have won a competitive match at the national stadium.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The board has developed the stadium in recent years, adding a function hall so that sponsors and match-goers can enjoy licensed and catering facilities.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] In Buckpool, next door to Buckpool Golf Club, is Merson Park, home of Buckie Rovers Football Club.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] *The Rovers* are members of the Scottish Junior Football Association and play in that body's North First Division (East).
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] At one time they played at Victoria Park, alternating home fixtures with their senior cousins but when Buckie Thistle were suffering an episode of extreme financial distress the decision was taken to move to a new facility at the municipal Merson Park.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The Merson Park ground has only a perimeter fence and dugouts differentiating it from a municipal pitch and there are no covered or seated facilities.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Near the southern edge of town on High Street lies Linzee Gordon Park.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] This is home to Buckie Cricket Club, which has a very long history with numerous Macallan North of Scotland Cricket Association League titles (having last topped the league in 2018) on top of various league and cup wins in the 1990s including two wins in the Scottish Cricket Union Small Clubs Cup.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The club built a modern pavilion to replace their aging home, which opened in June 1998.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The construction was partly funded by sportscotland and the National Lottery.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Linzee Gordon Park also has a municipal pavilion along with a pitch for football use.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie Bowling Club is on North High Street and Low Street with views over the Moray Firth from the clubhouse.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie Victoria Bowling Club is at the end of West Church Street, near the Buckpool bridge.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The town also has a 25m swimming pool next to Buckie High School, which opened in 1975.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Buckie is at the end of the Speyside Way long-distance footpath.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] There are "marvellous landscapes" all along the Banff coast, with easy access to areas such as Glenlivet, Speyside and the Cairngorms.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] Stephen King mentioned Buckie Thistle in his novella collection *If It Bleeds*.
[src:seafield-hospital/buckie] The author later posed wearing a Buckie Thistle football strip and scarf gifted by the football club.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Chalmers Hospital was founded by Alexander Chalmers (died 11 August 1835), a merchant of Banff, who left the whole of his estate to be applied, upon the death of his wife, towards funding and building a hospital for the people in the Royal Burgh of Banff.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Mrs Chalmers died in 1861, and Chalmers Hospital opened on 19 July 1864.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The original 'deed of mortification' set out that this was for any destitute sick persons born, domiciled or resident in the Banff area, although in 1929 the trustees successfully petitioned for the removal of this restriction.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Some major redevelopment work began in October 2008, after the hospital attracted criticism for not being up to date, with some of the interior features having been there since the Second World War.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital remained open during the work, although the Findlater ward services were moved to Campbell Hospital in Portsoy until the Findlater ward was refurbished, and Seafield and Deveron ward were merged.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The midwifery unit was demolished and rebuilt to provide modern facilities.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] Numerous other internal changes were also made inside, including X-ray facilities being moved to a different area of the building.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The redevelopment also provided upgraded facilities for physiotherapy, occupational therapy, speech and language therapy and podiatry.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The completion of the redevelopment was recognised with a visit by the Princess Royal in March 2012.
[src:seafield-hospital/chalmers-hospital-banff] The hospital is supported by GPs from Banff, Gamrie, Deveron, Macduff, Portsoy and Aberchirder Medical Practices.
[src:seafield-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] The facility, which was designed by William Smith, was established as an infectious diseases hospital in 1874.
[src:seafield-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] It was significantly expanded in 1895 and a new nurses' home was completed in 1931.
[src:seafield-hospital/city-hospital-aberdeen] During the 1964 Aberdeen typhoid outbreak, over 400 cases were diagnosed and the patients were quarantined at the City Hospital and Woodend Hospital, although no fatalities resulted.
[src:seafield-hospital/seafield-hospital] The hospital was officially opened as Rathven Parish Hospital in 1911.
[src:seafield-hospital/seafield-hospital] It was expanded in 1919 and 1930 and, after joining the National Health Service in 1948, it was extended again in 1964.
[src:seafield-hospital/seafield-hospital] By this time the hospital was known as Seafield Hospital.
[src:seafield-hospital/seafield-hospital] It was refurbished in 2001 and the front doors were replaced in 2004.
[src:seafield-hospital/seafield-hospital] Seafield Hospital has 32 beds providing medical care, rehabilitation, assessment, palliative/terminal care, convalescence and respite care.
